abstract.text: Pelvic floor morbidity up to one year after difficult instrumental delivery and cesarean section in the second stage of labor: A cohort study 4 Rachel E. Liebling, MRCOG, Rebecca Swingler, MB, ChB, Roshni R. Patel, MRCOG, Lisa Verity, MRCOG, Peter W. Soothill, MD, FRCOG, Deirdre J. Murphy, MD, MRCOG Bath, Bristol, Plymouth, and Dundee, United Kingdom
Women are more likely to report significant symptoms related to pelvic floor morbidity after ÔdifficultÕ instrumental vaginal deliveries compared with cesarean section at full dilatation.

This is one of a flurry of articles on the long-term consequences of various aspects of vaginal delivery, in this case, operative vaginal delivery. The accompanying editorial by Dr Hurt has identified the concerns in this article, which are both current and have meaning for the ethics and morality of what we have been taught. It raises serious questions for the future. With the conflict between the concern for controlling unnecessary cesarean sections, the pendulum swinging away from VBAC, and now with ACOG endorsing primary elective cesarean delivery as a patient's option, the information in this and other similar articles becomes crucial in trying to make sense of this dilemma.
A maternal serum vitamin B 12 concentration of < 185 pmol/L is associated with a 3.5-fold increased risk of an offspring with spina bifida.
Advanced age was associated with continued pessary use; stage III-IV rectocele and desire for surgery were associated with discontinued pessary use and surgery.
Women without pubococcygeal muscle are half as likely to increase urethral closure pressure during a pelvic muscle contraction compared with women with bilaterally intact muscle.
Satisfaction after the tension-free vaginal tape sling procedure is most dependent on subjective success and normal bladder storage and voiding function.

body_text.text: Pregnancies after treatment for fibromyomata with uterine artery embolization, compared with pregnancies after laparoscopic myomectomy, are at increased risk for preterm delivery and malpresentation.

Uterine artery embolization (UAE) became a minimally invasive alternative to traditional treatment of uterine leiomyomas, hysterectomy, or myomectomy, especially for women desiring future fertility. Few studies looked at complication rates and pregnancy outcomes after UAE compared to myomectomy. The authors of this paper report an increased risk for preterm labor and malpresentation in pregnancies following UAE compared to laparoscopic myomectomy. Although it is an observational, non-randomized retrospective study of heterogeneous population, the findings are clinically important in counseling patients.

Outcome of uterine embolization and hysterectomy for leiomyomas: Results of a multicenter study Uterine embolization and hysterectomy are both effective in controlling the symptoms that are associated with uterine leiomyomas, with few serious complications.

Uterine artery embolization (UAE) for the treatment of symptomatic myomas is a relatively new therapy. Although numerous case series have been reported on the outcome of UAE, little is known regarding the relative effectiveness compared with traditional surgical treatment and long-term outcomes for the quality of life following the procedure. This prospective multicenter study addresses an important topic by looking at quality of life outcomes for patients undergoing UAE or hysterectomy for symptoms resulting from uterine myomas. The authors report the effectiveness of UAE and that UAE and hysterectomy are equally effective and safe. It is reassuring that this new procedure offers an alternative approach for patients and gynecologists.
